wiki_catalogs.name: System Overview
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive content for this section focused on the MCP Nexus desktop application. Explain its purpose as a centralized management tool for Model Context Protocol (MCP) servers across multiple AI clients, enabling secure credential storage, automatic configuration synchronization, and health monitoring. Describe the hybrid architecture combining a React 19 frontend with a Rust backend via the Tauri framework. Highlight key capabilities such as server installation from multiple sources (npm, uvx, GitHub, Docker), client auto-sync, marketplace integration with PulseMCP API, and macOS Keychain-backed credential security. Illustrate the high-level data flow from UI components through React Query hooks to Tauri commands and Rust services. Include diagrams showing component relationships and system context. Provide real-world use cases for AI developers managing local MCP servers, and explain how the application simplifies complex configuration workflows. Ensure terminology aligns with codebase conventions like McpServer, DetectedClient, and SyncEngine.

wiki_catalogs.name: Marketplace Browsing
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the marketplace browsing experience in MCP Nexus. Explain how the MarketplaceCard component renders server listings with metadata such as name, description, version, author, and category. Document the integration between the useMarketplace hook and the Rust-based MarketplaceClient service that fetches and caches server manifests from the PulseMCP API. Describe the ServerDetailModal that provides in-depth information including usage examples, prerequisites, and environment requirements. Include examples of server manifest structure and categorization logic. Address UI/UX considerations such as loading states, error handling for failed fetches, and visual indicators for verified publishers. Provide guidance on optimizing performance through data pagination and lazy loading of server details.

wiki_catalogs.name: Supported Clients
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the supported clients feature in the client synchronization system. Explain how the ClientDetector service identifies installed AI development environments such as VS Code, JetBrains IDEs, and other compatible editors by scanning standard installation paths and registry entries across operating systems. Document the detection logic, including file system traversal, process inspection, and configuration file validation. Describe the Client model structure that captures client metadata like name, path, version, and configuration schema. Provide examples of detection patterns for each supported client and explain how new clients can be added to the detection system. Include troubleshooting guidance for common detection failures such as permission issues, non-standard installations, and version incompatibilities. Address performance considerations for minimizing detection latency during startup and sync operations.

Include practical examples of modifying these files to enable new features, adjust build targets, or optimize performance. Address common configuration errors, version compatibility issues, and best practices for maintaining cross-platform consistency. Explain integration with the build pipeline and how changes affect development vs. production environments.

wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create architectural documentation for the MCP Nexus frontend architecture. Describe the React 19 component-based structure organized by domain (servers, clients, marketplace, etc.), with clear separation between presentational and container components. Detail the state management strategy using Zustand stores (appStore, notificationStore) for global state and React Query for server state management. Explain the custom hooks architecture that abstracts Tauri command interactions and provides data fetching, caching, and synchronization capabilities. Document the UI component organization with reusable common components and domain-specific components. Include diagrams showing component hierarchy, data flow from hooks to components, and the React Query caching strategy. Address error boundary implementation, toast notification system, and keyboard event handling. Explain the integration between Tailwind CSS and the component styling approach.

Cover command groups: server installation and management (install_server, uninstall_server), client synchronization (sync_to_client, detect_clients), health monitoring (check_health), credential operations (save_credential, get_credential), marketplace interactions (get_marketplace_servers, get_server_details), and update management (check_for_updates). Explain the type safety between frontend TypeScript interfaces and Rust structs, highlighting shared models like McpServer and MarketplaceServer. Address error handling patterns, loading states, and async behavior in the context of React Query integration.

Explain the custom error types defined in the application (e.g., InstallationError, SyncError, HealthCheckError) and their hierarchical structure using Rust's error handling patterns. Document how errors are propagated from services through commands to the frontend using Tauri's Result type. Describe the error conversion process to frontend-friendly formats with appropriate error codes and messages. Include examples of error handling in service implementations, command wrappers, and top-level error boundaries. Address logging strategies using tracing macros, error categorization (recoverable vs. fatal), and user-facing error presentation through Toast notifications. Explain how error contexts are preserved across async boundaries and how partial failures (e.g., sync to some clients) are handled gracefully. Provide troubleshooting guidance for common error scenarios and debugging techniques using log levels and structured logging.

wiki_catalogs.name: DetectedClient Model
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Document the DetectedClient data model that represents AI development environments detected on the user's system. Detail fields including client_type, installation_path, configuration_path, and supported MCP versions. Explain how this model is populated by the ClientDetector service during system scans and how it enables client-specific configuration synchronization. Describe Serde serialization for persistence and IPC transfer to the frontend. Provide examples of how different clients (e.g., Claude Desktop, VS Code) are represented and how their configuration paths are used during sync operations. Discuss validation logic for path integrity and version compatibility checks. Illustrate the relationship between DetectedClient and McpServer in the context of configuration file generation and deployment.

wiki_catalogs.name: Keychain Service
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the Keychain service. Thoroughly explain its implementation details, including secure credential storage and retrieval using macOS Keychain, error handling for access violations, and integration with the credential management system. Document the service's interface methods, their parameters, and return values, with concrete examples from the codebase showing credential storage and validation workflows. Explain how the service handles permission requests, ensures data encryption, and manages credential lifecycle. Address common issues such as access denied errors, keychain corruption, and migration scenarios, providing troubleshooting guidance. Include security best practices for credential handling and compliance with platform security guidelines.

wiki_catalogs.name: Credential Management Commands
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create API documentation for the credential management command handlers in MCP Nexus. Document the store_credential, get_credential, and delete_credential functions, including their parameters (credential ID, service identifier, access rules), return types (success status, credential data), and error cases (access denied, keychain locked, invalid credentials). Explain how these commands interface with the KeychainService to provide secure storage using macOS Keychain. Include examples of frontend invocation from CredentialManager and CredentialInput components. Detail the encryption mechanisms, access control policies, and audit logging for credential operations. Address security considerations such as biometric authentication integration, secure memory handling, and protection against brute force attacks. Reference the usage in server configuration and environment variable resolution.

wiki_catalogs.name: UVX Installation

Document the Python/uv runtime validation, package installation via uvx, and argument handling. Detail the transport configuration building logic for uvx sources, including environment variable injection and Python environment setup. wiki_overview.content:
<blog>
# Comprehensive Project Analysis: MCP Nexus

## 1. Project Introduction

MCP Nexus is a desktop application designed to manage Model Context Protocol (MCP) servers across multiple AI clients including Claude Code, Claude Desktop, Cursor, Cline, VS Code, Continue, Windsurf, and Warp. Built with Tauri (Rust backend) and React (TypeScript frontend), it provides centralized configuration management, marketplace integration, secure credential storage via macOS Keychain, and automatic syncing across multiple AI platforms.

**Core Goals and Objectives:**
- Centralize MCP server management across 8+ AI clients
- Provide a unified interface for server installation, configuration, and monitoring
- Enable secure credential management using macOS Keychain
- Automate configuration synchronization across different client formats
- Offer health monitoring and update notifications for managed servers

**Target Audience:**
- AI developers and researchers using multiple AI clients
- Teams managing MCP servers across different development environments
- Users requiring secure credential management for AI tools
- Developers seeking to streamline their AI workflow across multiple platforms

## 2. Technical Architecture

### Component Breakdown

The MCP Nexus application follows a hybrid architecture combining a Rust backend with a React frontend, connected through the Tauri framework. This architecture provides native performance with a modern web-based UI.

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    A[React Frontend] --> B[Tauri Bridge]
    B --> C[Rust Backend]
    C --> D[OS Services]
    D --> E[(macOS Keychain)]
    D --> F[(File System)]
    D --> G[(Network)]
    A --> H[(User Interface)]
```

### Design Patterns

The application employs several key design patterns:

- **Layered Architecture**: Clear separation between presentation (React), business logic (Rust services), and data access layers
- **Command Pattern**: Tauri commands provide a clean API between frontend and backend
- **React Query for State Management**: Server state is managed with React Query while client state uses Zustand
- **Error Boundary Pattern**: Comprehensive error handling with fallback UIs
- **Dependency Injection**: Services are properly encapsulated and injected where needed

### System Relationships

The system consists of two main components that communicate through the Tauri bridge:

```mermaid
graph TD
    Frontend[React Frontend] -->|Tauri Commands| Backend[Rust Backend]
    Backend -->|Keyring| Keychain[macOS Keychain]
    Backend -->|File I/O| FileSystem[File System]
    Backend -->|HTTP Requests| API[PulseMCP API]
    Frontend -->|React Query| Cache[Client Cache]
    Frontend -->|Zustand| Store[Global State]
```

### Data Flow

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    A[User Interaction] --> B[React Component]
    B --> C[React Hook]
    C --> D[React Query Mutation]
    D --> E[Tauri Command]
    E --> F[Rust Command Handler]
    F --> G[Rust Service]
    G --> H[Data Access]
    H --> I[(Persistent Storage)]
    I --> J[Rust Service Response]
    J --> K[Rust Command Response]
    K --> L[Tauri Response]
    L --> M[React Query Update]
    M --> N[State Update]
    N --> O[UI Update]
```

## 3. Key Implementation

### Main Entry Points
- `src/main.tsx` - React entry point
- `src/App.tsx` - Main application component with routing
- `src-tauri/src/main.rs` - Rust application entry point
- `src-tauri/src/lib.rs` - Tauri app initialization

### Core Modules
- **Frontend**: React 19 with TypeScript, React Router for navigation, React Query for server state, Zustand for client state
- **Backend**: Rust with Tauri 2.0, Tokio async runtime, Serde for serialization
- **Services**: Config management, sync engine, marketplace client, installation service, health checks

### Configuration Approach
The application uses a combination of build-time and runtime configuration:

- **Build Configuration**: Vite, TypeScript, ESLint, Prettier
- **Runtime Configuration**: Central config at `~/.mcp-nexus/config.json`, user preferences, environment variables
- **Tauri Configuration**: `tauri.conf.json` for app settings, security policies, and bundling

### External Dependencies
- **Frontend**: React 19, React Query, Zustand, Tailwind CSS
- **Backend**: Tauri, Tokio, Reqwest, Keyring, Serde
- **Development**: Vitest, React Testing Library, ESLint, Prettier

### Integration Points
- **Tauri Bridge**: Communication between React and Rust
- **macOS Keychain**: Secure credential storage
- **PulseMCP API**: Marketplace integration
- **AI Client Configs**: File system integration for client configuration files

### Component Relationships

```mermaid
graph LR
    App[App Component] --> Router[React Router]
    Router --> Dashboard[Dashboard Page]
    Router --> Marketplace[Marketplace Page]
    Router --> Servers[Servers Page]
    Router --> Clients[Clients Page]
    Router --> Settings[Settings Page]
    
    Dashboard --> Summary[Summary Cards]
    Dashboard --> QuickActions[Quick Actions]
    Dashboard --> RecentActivity[Recent Activity]
    
    Marketplace --> Search[Search Bar]
    Marketplace --> Filters[Filter Panel]
    Marketplace --> Sort[Sort Dropdown]
    Marketplace --> Cards[Marketplace Cards]
    Marketplace --> Modal[Server Detail Modal]
    
    Servers --> List[Server List]
    Servers --> AddModal[Add Server Modal]
    Servers --> Cards[Server Cards]
    
    Clients --> List[Client List]
    Clients --> Sync[Sync Status]
    Clients --> Manual[Manual Config]
    
    Settings --> Credentials[Credential Manager]
    Settings --> Environment[Environment Status]
    
    App --> Sidebar[Navigation Sidebar]
    App --> Header[Page Header]
    App --> Toast[Toast Notifications]
    App --> ErrorBoundary[Error Boundary]
```

## 4. Key Features

### Functionality Overview

MCP Nexus provides comprehensive management of MCP servers across multiple AI clients with the following key features:

1. **Server Management**: Install, configure, and manage MCP servers from various sources
2. **Client Synchronization**: Automatically sync server configurations to supported AI clients
3. **Marketplace Integration**: Browse and discover MCP servers through the PulseMCP API
4. **Health Monitoring**: Check server health status with response time metrics
5. **Credential Management**: Securely store credentials using macOS Keychain
6. **Update Notifications**: Track available updates for managed servers
7. **Environment Detection**: Detect required runtimes and dependencies

### Implementation Highlights

The application implements several sophisticated features that demonstrate its robust architecture:

```mermaid
stateDiagram-v2
    [*] --> Idle
    Idle --> Initializing: App Start
    Initializing --> Ready: Config Loaded
    Initializing --> Error: Initialization Failed
    
    Ready --> Browsing: Navigate to Marketplace
    Browsing --> Installing: Select Server
    Installing --> Installing: Process Installation
    Installing --> Success: Installation Complete
    Installing --> Error: Installation Failed
    
    Ready --> Managing: Navigate to Servers
    Managing --> Adding: Add Server
    Managing --> Syncing: Sync to Clients
    Managing --> Monitoring: Check Health
    Managing --> Updating: Apply Updates
    
    Ready --> Configuring: Navigate to Settings
    Configuring --> ManagingCredentials: Add/Edit Credentials
    Configuring --> SettingPreferences: Update Preferences
    
    Error --> Recovering: User Action
    Recovering --> Ready: Success
    Recovering --> Error: Failure
```

### Feature Architecture

The application's feature architecture demonstrates a clean separation of concerns between the frontend and backend components:

```mermaid
graph TD
    subgraph Frontend
        A[React Components] --> B[React Hooks]
        B --> C[React Query]
        C --> D[Tauri Commands]
    end
    
    subgraph Backend
        D --> E[Rust Commands]
        E --> F[Rust Services]
        F --> G[Rust Models]
        G --> H[Data Access]
    end
    
    H --> I[(macOS Keychain)]
    H --> J[(File System)]
    H --> K[(Network API)]
    
    style Frontend fill:#f0f8ff,stroke:#333
    style Backend fill:#e6f3ff,stroke:#333
```

The frontend components are organized into a logical structure with reusable components, domain-specific components, and page-level components. The backend follows a clean layered architecture with commands handling Tauri invocations, services implementing business logic, and models defining data structures.

This architecture enables the application to provide a seamless user experience while maintaining robust security and reliability through proper error handling, secure credential storage, and comprehensive testing.
</blog>
